topic.title: Header Insertion and Extraction

body.p: Each packet to/from the MCPB has an additional header (VLAN tag plus additional bytes) applied to it, forming an internal "augmented frame". The header carries critical timing information about the packet, control or identification information about the packets between the ENET and the Internal CPU.

The Extraction Path (ingress extract, egress extract or reflection port) adds a proprietary VLAN Tag, timestamp information and packet classification information. The Device-proprietary Header format, via the TS_INCLUDE control, will include or exclude timestamp information. The FEPP_I (Ingress) block makes use of both Device-proprietary Header possibilities, while the FEPP_E Egress block only issues packets without timestamp information. The ETIME block (reflection path) always includes the timestamp, but will always zero the classification tag. All Device-proprietary Header bit fields are described below.

entry.p: 0: No VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet.
1: One VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet.
2: Double VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet

row.entry: Page Number (FEPP_I) or Reserved (FEPP_E) or Sequence ID (ETIME)

entry.p: 0: ToD and CFC not present in forwarded packet
1: ToD and CFC present in forwarded packet

body.p: The figure below depicts the input frame format, Frame A, and possible packet output formats from the Header Insertion block. Frame B is output if the Timestamp Included bit is set in the VLAN TCI bit 0, while Frame C is output when that bit is 0. All frames are depicted with Inner and Outer VLAN tags as well as FCS, although these fields may or may not be present in the packet. The VLAN state information, provided in the device-proprietary Header, provides the processor a quick check to identify if, and how many, VLAN tags are present.

fig.title: Frame Format Through Ingress Header Insertion Block

body.p: The Insert Path (Header Extraction) removes the proprietary VLAN Tag from the packet.

For inserted packets, the format differs for ingress insert and egress insert. This is because for the egress insert, instructions on what to do with the packet are included (timestamp instructions, FCS calculation instructions). Meanwhile, packets inserted into the ingress datapath (towards the Data Central Packet Buffer) have no such instructions.
In the Egress direction, the Header Extraction block extracts the following device-proprietary Header information from the received packet:

table.title: Egress Direction Device-proprietary Header Bit Fields

entry.p: 0: No VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet.
1: One VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet.
2: Double VLAN tag in received Ethernet packet

body.p: The figure below shows the frame format through Egress header extraction block, where Frame A depicts the received frame, while Frame B depicts the outgoing packet with the device-proprietary Header removed. The frame may be received with, or without, optional VLAN Tags and FCS.

fig.title: Frame Format Through Egress Header Extraction Block

body.p: The Egress Header extraction block, after the extraction of above mentioned control header fields, will not recompute, nor will it append an FCS field to the outgoing packet.
In the Ingress direction, the Header Extraction block extracts the following device-proprietary Header information from the received packet:

table.title: Igress Direction Device-proprietary Header Bit Fields

fig.title: Frame Format Through Ingress Header Extraction Block

body.p: The figure above Frame format -A shows the Ethernet Packet inserted through Ingress Insert port, whereas Frame format-B shows the output of Ingress Header Extraction block (VLAN Tag extracted) before the packet is forwarded to the DCPB.

The Ingress Header Extractor extracts a 3-bit priority from the device-proprietary Header. This 3-bit priority is used to determine the Data CPB channel onto which the packet is destined. This feature is not required for this device.
Note that the optional FCS must be calculated by the CPU prior to inclusion of the device-proprietary Header as the EMPEI Ingress block will not recalculate the FCS of the outgoing packet.
